  = [[Bologna]], [[Italy]]\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1      = 1979\u20131980\n| proteam1       = [[Bianchi cycling team|San Giacomo-Mobilificio]]\n| proyears2      = 1982\n| proteam2       = [[Bardiani\u2013CSF|Termolan-Galli]]\n| proyears3      = 1983\u20131988\n| proteam3       = [[Alfa Lum cycling team|Alfa Lum-Olmo]]\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Orlando Maini''' (born 17 December 1958 in [[Bologna]]) is a former Italian cyclist.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=174538 | title=Orlando Maini | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> He rode in 11 [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]].\n\n==Palmares==\n;1984\n:1st Stage 9 [[1984 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n;1985\n:1st Stage 7 [[1985 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maini, Orlando}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a stage winners]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bologna]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orlando_Maini"}
{"title_page": "Loudoun Academy of Science", "text_new": "\n\n{{infobox School\n|name= Academies of Loudoun\n|type= [[Magnet school]]\n|location= 42075 Academy Drive<br>Leesburg, VA 20175\n|coordinates = {{coord|39.042637| -77.550348|display=inline}}\n| pushpin_map = USA Virginia Northern#USA Virginia#USA\n|image=File:Academies of Loudoun from bus loop.jpg\n|motto=Explore, Research, Collaborate, Innovate\n|established= 2005\n|district= [[Loudoun County Public Schools]]\n|grades= 9-12\n|students=400-600 \n|athletics= None\n|colors=Blue and Green\n|mascot= Raptors\n|free_label= Principal of Academies\n|free_text= Tinell Priddy\n|free_label2= Director of AOS\n|free_text2= Jennifer Chang\n|information= 571-252-1980\n|website= [https://www.lcps.org/domain/23877 Official Webpage]\n}}\nThe '''Academy of Science''' is a STEM magnet program for high school students enrolled in [[Loudoun County Public Schools]].  The program was located at the campus of [[Dominion High School]] at 21326 Augusta Drive in [[Sterling, Virginia|Sterling]], an area in unincorporated [[Loudoun County, Virginia]]. During the summer of 2018, the Academy of Science became a division of the [[Academies of Loudoun]], located at 42075 Academy Drive in Leesburg, VA.  The Academies of Loudoun include the [[Loudoun Academy of Engineering & Technology]], The Loudoun Academy of Science, and [[Monroe Advanced Technical Academy]].\n\n==History and structure==\nThe Academy of Science program was established in 2005 as a magnet program of science and technology for Loudoun County students. \nThe purpose of the Academy is to provide advanced academic math and science courses for students interested in STEM.  These courses include [[Advanced Placement]] courses, as well as classes devoted purely towards scientific research.\n\n==Admissions==\nThe admissions process is extraordinarily competitive for 8th graders who wish to attend the Academies of Loudoun. As the AOS science, math, and research curriculum has gained popularity over the years, the number of applicants has soared. Prior to 2018, 68 students would enroll each year which resulted in an acceptance rate of approximately 7%, making admission highly competitive. Once the Academy became part of the Academies of Loudoun building, additional classroom space and teaching faculty allowed 120 9th graders to enroll each year.\n\n==Extracurricular activities and athletics==\nAll students who attend the Academies of Loudoun every other school day where they take courses in math, science, and research. On alternating days, Academy students attend their home school, where they take courses in English, Social Studies, and other electives.  The Loudoun County High Schools try to coordinate their schedules to allow Academy students to take extra curricular classes at the home school, but scheduling conflicts often arise.  Students who attend the Academies of Loudoun are concurrently enrolled in both their home school and the Academies of Loudoun.\n\nAcademy students who are on athletic teams play for their home schools and their respective conferences.\n\n==Research==\nMost of the Academy of Science curriculum is based on a junior/senior year research project. After a topic is chosen and approved, students work with a large spectrum of different lab devices and their mentor to further develop this research project. Students also are given the option to apply for a collaboration project with students of Hwa Chong Institution in Singapore, or Daegu Science High School in South Korea. Participants in this program are then presented the opportunity to travel to Singapore/Korea for a research competition. \n\nIn past years, students have developed numerous research projects that have been exceptionally successful\u2014some of these had research papers were published, while others went on to place in many large science competitions such as the Siemens Westinghouse Science and Technology Competition, the Junior Science and Humanities Symposium, and the [[Intel ISEF]] competition.\n\n==Expansion==\nThe Academy of Science was originally at [[Dominion High School]] in [[Sterling, Virginia|Sterling]]. In the summer of 2018, the program became part of the [[Academies of Loudoun]] at 42075 Loudoun Academy Drive, [[Leesburg, Virginia|Leesburg]]. The principal of the Academies of Loudoun is Tinell Priddy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lcps.org/site/Default.aspx?PageID=196070|title=Administration / Dr. Tinell Priddy|website=www.lcps.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>, and the director of the Academy of Science is Jennifer Chang.\n\nThe mission of the Academies of Loudoun is to empower students to explore, research, collaborate, and innovate, and to make meaningful contributions to the world in the fields of science, technology, engineering and mathematics.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lcps.org/site/default.aspx?PageID=154616|title=Academies of Loudoun / Homepage|website=www.lcps.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> \n\n{{Coord|39|1|33.4|N|77|22|26.4|W|display=title}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Schools in Loudoun County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Magnet schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Alternative schools in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{infobox School\n|name= Academies of Loudoun\n|type= [[Magnet school]]\n|location= 42075 Academy Drive<br>Leesburg, VA 20175\n|coordinates = {{coord|39.042637| -77.550348|display=inline}}\n| pushpin_map = USA Virginia Northern#USA Virginia#USA\n|image=File:Academies of Loudoun from bus loop.jpg\n|motto= \n|established= 2005\n|district= [[Loudoun County Public Schools]]\n|grades= 9-12\n|students=370 \n|athletics= None\n|colors=Blue and Green\n|mascot= Raptors\n|free_label= Principal of Academies\n|free_text= Tinell Priddy\n|free_label2= Director of AOS\n|free_text2= Jennifer Chang\n|information= 571-252-1980\n|website= [http://www.lcps.org/acl Official Webpage]\n}}\nThe '''Academy of Science''' is a STEM magnet program for high school students enrolled in [[Loudoun County Public Schools]].  The program was located at the campus of [[Dominion High School]] at 21326 Augusta Drive in [[Sterling, Virginia|Sterling]], an area in unincorporated [[Loudoun County, Virginia]]. During the summer of 2018, the Academy of Science became a division of the [[Academies of Loudoun]], located at 42075 Academy Drive in Leesburg, VA.  The Academies of Loudoun include the [[Loudoun Academy of Engineering & Technology]], The Loudoun Academy of Science, and [[Monroe Advanced Technical Academy]].\n\n==History and structure==\nThe Academy of Science program was established in 2005 as a magnet program of science and technology for Loudoun County students. \nThe purpose of the Academy is to provide advanced academic math and science courses for students interested in STEM.  These courses include [[Advanced Placement]] courses, as well as classes devoted purely towards scientific research.\n\n==Admissions==\nThe admissions process is extraordinarily competitive for 8th graders who wish to attend the Academies of Loudoun. As the AOS science, math, and research curriculum has gained popularity over the years, the number of applicants has soared. Prior to 2018, 68 students would enroll each year which resulted in an acceptance rate of approximately 7%, making admission highly competitive. Once the Academy became part of the Academies of Loudoun building, additional classroom space and teaching faculty allowed 120 9th graders to enroll each year.\n\n==Extracurricular activities and athletics==\nAll students who attend the Academies of Loudoun every other school day where they take courses in math, science, and research. On alternating days, Academy students attend their home school, where they take courses in English, Social Studies, and other electives.  The Loudoun County High Schools try to coordinate their schedules to allow Academy students to take extra curricular classes at the home school, but scheduling conflicts often arise.  Students who attend the Academies of Loudoun are concurrently enrolled in both their home school and the Academies of Loudoun.\n\nAcademy students who are on athletic teams play for their home schools and their respective conferences.\n\n==Research==\nMost of the Academy of Science curriculum is based on a junior/senior year research project. After a topic is chosen and approved, students work with a large spectrum of different lab devices and their mentor to further develop this research project. Students also are given the option to apply for a collaboration project with students of Hwa Chong Institution in Singapore, or Daegu Science High School in South Korea. Participants in this program are then presented the opportunity to travel to Singapore/Korea for a research competition. \n\nIn past years, students have developed numerous research projects that have been exceptionally successful\u2014some of these had research papers were published, while others went on to place in many large science competitions such as the Siemens Westinghouse Science and Technology Competition, the Junior Science and Humanities Symposium, and the [[Intel ISEF]] competition.\n\n==Expansion==\nThe Academy of Science was originally at [[Dominion High School]] in [[Sterling, Virginia|Sterling]]. In the summer of 2018, the program became part of the [[Academies of Loudoun]] at 42075 Loudoun Academy Drive, [[Leesburg, Virginia|Leesburg]]. The principal of the Academies of Loudoun is Tinell Priddy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lcps.org/site/Default.aspx?PageID=196070|title=Administration / Dr. Tinell Priddy|website=www.lcps.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>, and the director of the Academy of Science is Jennifer Chang.\n\nThe mission of the Academies of Loudoun is to empower students to explore, research, collaborate, and innovate, and to make meaningful contributions to the world in the fields of science, technology, engineering and mathematics.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lcps.org/site/default.aspx?PageID=154616|title=Academies of Loudoun / Homepage|website=www.lcps.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref> \n\n{{Coord|39|1|33.4|N|77|22|26.4|W|display=title}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Schools in Loudoun County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Magnet schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Alternative schools in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Chopper2112", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loudoun_Academy_of_Science"}
{"title_page": "Edmund Lenthal Swifte", "text_new": "[[File:Edmund Lental Swifte.jpg|thumb|Edmund Lenthal Swifte]]\n[[File:Tower of London (Foto Hilarmont).jpg|thumb|Tower of London]]\n'''Edmund Lewis Lenthal Swifte''' or '''Swift''' (20 June 1777 \u2013 28 December 1875) was a British lawyer, poet and writer who was for many years the custodian of the [[Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom|British Crown Jewels]] in the [[Tower of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/BiographyRecord.php?action=GET&bioid=4499|title=Edmund Lewis Swift Frederic Boase, Modern English Biography (1892-1921) 3:848-49.|accessdate= 26 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was born a younger son of Theophilus Swifte of [[Goodrich, Herefordshire]] (a relative of [[Jonathan Swift]]) and studied at [[Trinity College, Dublin]]. He was a member of the Lawyers' corps in Ireland (1796\u20131803) and was [[called to the bar]] in Dublin in 1803. He was called to the bar in England in 1815.\n\nIn 1814 he was appointed [[Master of the Jewel Office]] in the Tower of London, a position he held until 1852. During his time there (in October, 1817) he claimed to have seen a ghostly apparition floating above his wife's head at dinner.\n\nHe produced a number of poems, translations and essays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/AuthorRecord.php?action=GET&recordid=33365|title=Edmund Lewis Swift (1777-1875)|publisher= Spencerians|accessdate= 26 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe died in Dover in 1875 at the age of 98. He had married several times and had many children.\n\n==Works==\n* ''Life and acts of St. Patrick'' by Jocelin - translation, 1809\n* ''Anacreon in Dublin'' - poetry, 1814\n* ''Waterloo and other poems''- 1815\n* ''Juvenal's 10th and 13th Satires'' - translation, 1818.\n* ''The equality of the constitution'' - essay, 1819.\n* ''Woman's will \u2014 a riddle! An operatic drama'' - 1820.\n* ''One thousand eight hundred and twenty nine, or, shall it be so?'' -1829.\n* ''Homeric studies'' - 1840.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/opie-edmund-lenthal-swifte-n04066 Portrait of Edmund Lenthal Swifte]\n* [http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/TextRecord.php?action=GET&textsid=3602 Waterloo-a poem by Edmund Swifte]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swifte, Edmund Lenthal}}\n[[Category:1777 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Herefordshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:British poets]]\n[[Category:Masters of the Jewel Office]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Edmund Lental Swifte.jpg|thumb|Edmund Lenthal Swifte]]\n[[File:Tower of London (Foto Hilarmont).jpg|thumb|Tower of London]]\n'''Edmund Lewis Lenthal Swifte''' or '''Swift''' (20 June 1777 \u2013 28 December 1875) was a British lawyer, poet and writer who was for many years the custodian of the [[Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom|British Crown Jewels]] in the [[Tower of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/BiographyRecord.php?action=GET&bioid=4499|title=Edmund Lewis Swift Frederic Boase, Modern English Biography (1892-1921) 3:848-49.|accessdate= 26 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was born a younger son of Theophilus Swifte of [[Goodrich, Herefordshire]] (a relative of [[Jonathan Swift]]) and studied at [[Trinity College, Dublin]]. He was a member of the Lawyers' corps in Ireland (1796\u20131803) and was [[called to the bar]] in Dublin in 1803. He was called to the bar in England in 1815.\n\nIn 1814 he was appointed [[Master of the Jewel Office]] in the Tower of London, a position he held until 1852. During his time there (in October, 1817) he claimed to have seen a ghostly apparition floating above his wife's head at dinner.\n\nHe produced a number of poems, translations and essays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/AuthorRecord.php?action=GET&recordid=33365|title=Edmund Lewis Swift (1777-1875)|publisher= Spencerians|accessdate= 26 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe died in Dover in 1875 at the age of 98. He had married several times and had many children.\n\n==Works==\n* ''Life and acts of St. Patrick'' by Jocelin - translation, 1809\n* ''Anacreon in Dublin'' - poetry, 1814\n* ''Waterloo and other poems''- 1815\n* ''Juvenal's 10th and 13th Satires'' - translation, 1818.\n* ''The equality of the constitution'' - essay, 1819.\n* ''Woman's will \u2014 a riddle! An operatic drama'' - 1820.\n* ''One thousand eight hundred and twenty nine, or, shall it be so?'' -1829.\n* ''Homeric studies'' - 1840.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/opie-edmund-lenthal-swifte-n04066 Portrait of Edmund Lenthal Swifte]\n* [http://spenserians.cath.vt.edu/TextRecord.php?action=GET&textsid=3602 Waterloo-a poem by Edmund Swifte]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swifte, Edmund Lenthal}}\n[[Category:1777 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Herefordshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:British poets]]\n[[Category:Masters of the Jewel Office]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmund_Lenthal_Swifte"}
{"title_page": "Tim Boswell", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Boswell of Aynho\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Official portrait of Lord Boswell of Aynho crop 3.jpg\n| caption = Lord Boswell of Aynho in 2019\n| office = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister = [[John Major]]\n| term_start = 14 April 1992\n| term_end = 11 December 1992\n| predecessor = [[Sydney Chapman (politician)|Sydney Chapman]]\n| successor = [[Timothy Kirkhope]]\n|office1         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br />[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start1       = 8 July 2010<br />[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n|term_end1       =\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Daventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Daventry]]\n| parliament2 = \n| term_start2 = 12 June 1987\n| term_end2 = 12 April 2010\n| majority2 = \n| predecessor2 = [[Reg Prentice, Baron Prentice|Reg Prentice]]\n| successor2 = [[Chris Heaton-Harris]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1942|12|2|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Brentwood Urban District|Brentwood]], [[Essex]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = English\n| spouse = Helen Delahay Rees\n| party = Conservative\n| relations = \n| children = [[Victoria Prentis]]\n| residence = \n| education = [[Marlborough College]]\n| alma_mater = [[New College, Oxford]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Farmer and politician \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Timothy Eric Boswell, Baron Boswell of Aynho''' (born 2 December 1942) is an English politician who was formerly the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Daventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Daventry]] from [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]] until he stood down at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], after which he was raised to the [[House of Lords]] as a Conservative [[life peer]].<ref name=\"Boswell_London_Gazette_Lords\">{{London Gazette |issue=59487 |date=13 July 2010 |page=13285}}</ref><ref name=\"Boswell_Parliament_UK\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-boswell-of-aynho/352 |title = Lord Boswell of Aynho |website=Parliament.uk |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Boswell_Whos_Who\">{{cite web |title=Boswell of Aynho |url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-8174/version/6 |website=ukwhoswho.com |publisher=Who's Who |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nThe son of a farmer, Tim Boswell was educated at [[Marlborough College]] and [[New College, Oxford]], where he obtained a degree in [[Classics]] and a diploma in [[agriculture|agricultural]] [[economics]].<ref name=\"Boswell_Whos_Who\"/>\n\nBoswell was married to Helen Delahay Boswell, n\u00e9e Rees, for 50 years until her death in 2019.<ref name=\"Boswell_Whos_Who\"/><ref name=\"Gazette_Helen_Boswell\">{{cite web |title=Helen Boswell - Deceased Estates |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/3398899 |website=The Gazette (Official Public Record) |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Legacy_Helen_Boswell\">{{cite web |title=Helen Boswell Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/amp/obituaries/thetimes-uk/193460817 |website=Legacy.com |publisher=The Times |accessdate=14 November 2019 |date=23 July 2019}}</ref> They had three daughters together including the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] [[Victoria Prentis]].\n\n==Political career==\n===Conservative Party===\nHe joined the [[Conservative Research Department]] in 1966, becoming head of the economics section in 1974. He stood for [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] at the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]] in [[Rugby (UK Parliament constituency)|Rugby]] but lost by 6,154 votes to [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s [[William Price (Rugby MP)|William Price]].\n\nHe was elected as the Treasurer of the Daventry Conservative Association in 1976 and subsequently its Chairman from 1979\u20131983. He became a political advisor to the [[Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] [[Michael Jopling, Baron Jopling|Michael Jopling]] for two years from 1984.\n\n===House of Commons===\nBoswell was chosen to contest the Daventry constituency after the sitting Conservative MP and former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Cabinet (government)|Cabinet]] member [[Reg Prentice]] had announced his retirement. Tim Boswell was elected as the Conservative MP for Daventry at the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]] with a majority of 19,690 and held the seat very comfortably since.\n\nTim Boswell's [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]] career began unsurprisingly as a Member of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Agriculture]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]] in 1987. He became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary to the Treasury#Financial Secretaries to the Treasury, 1852-present|Financial Secretary to the Treasury]] [[Peter Lilley]] in 1989. Tim Boswell entered [[John Major]]'s government in 1990 as an [[Whip (politics)|Assistant Government Whip]], following the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]] he was promoted within the Whip's Office and became a Lord Commissioner to the Treasury.\n\nIn December 1992, Tim Boswell was appointed [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department of Education]] and moved in the same position at the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] until the Major government fell at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].\n\nIn opposition Boswell was a spokesman on the [[HM Treasury|Treasury]] in the immediate aftermath of the 1997 election defeat and became a spokesman on [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Trade and Industry]] under [[William Hague]], before speaking on [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Education and Employment]] in 1999 until after the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]]. He became the spokesman for [[Department of Work and Pensions|Work and Pensions]] under the leadership of [[Iain Duncan Smith]], moving briefly to speak on [[Department of Constitutional Affairs|Constitutional Affairs]] in 2003 under [[Michael Howard]] and back to Work and Pensions in 2004, where he remained following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\nOn 31 March 2006, Boswell announced his intention not to contest the subsequent general election, provided it did not take place unexpectedly soon. The Daventry seat was split in two at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], with the northern portion becoming part of a new Daventry constituency and the southern part becoming part of a [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] constituency.\n\nIn May 2009, he was listed by ''The Telegraph'' as one of the \"Saints\" in the expenses scandal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5350793/MPs-expenses-The-saints-Part-iii.html?image=9|title=MPs' Expenses: the saints|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=1 July 2009|location=London|date=19 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter his retirement from the House of Commons the seat remained Conservative under [[Chris Heaton-Harris]].\n\n===House of Lords===\nHe was raised to the [[House of Lords]] as a Conservative [[Life peer]] being created '''Baron Boswell of Aynho''', of [[Aynho]] in the County of [[Northamptonshire]] on 8 July 2010.<ref name=\"Boswell_London_Gazette_Lords\"/> In May 2012, he resigned the Conservative whip after being made Principal Deputy Chairman of Committees in the House. He also became Chairman of the [[European Union Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/25724|title=Lord Boswell of Aynho biography|accessdate=12 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302182756/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/25724|archivedate=2 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/hleu|title=Lords European Union Committee homepage|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nOn 10 March 2016, Boswell was elected a [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London]] (FSA).<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Mar Ballot Results|url=https://www.sal.org.uk/news/2016/03/10-mar-ballot-results/|website=Society of Antiquaries of London|accessdate=16 April 2016|date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Tim+Boswell/ ePolitix.com - Tim Boswell MP]\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-tim-boswell | Tim Boswell }}\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-515,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Tim Boswell MP]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100409065917/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Boswell_Tim.aspx Profile] on Conservative Party website\n*[http://www.daventryconservatives.com Daventry Conservatives]\n*[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/tim_boswell/daventry TheyWorkForYou.com - Tim Boswell MP]\n*[http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Tim_Boswell&mpc=Daventry The Public Whip - Tim Boswell MP] voting record\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/130.stm BBC News - Tim Boswell] profile 15 February 2005\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Daventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Daventry]]\n  