place = [[Brentwood Urban District|Brentwood]], [[Essex]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = English\n| spouse = Helen Delahay Rees\n| party = Conservative\n| relations = \n| children = [[Victoria Prentis]]\n| residence = \n| education = [[Marlborough College]]\n| alma_mater = [[New College, Oxford]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Farmer and politician \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Timothy Eric Boswell, Baron Boswell of Aynho''' (born 2 December 1942) is an English politician who was formerly the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Daventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Daventry]] from [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]] until he stood down at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], after which he was raised to the [[House of Lords]] as a Conservative [[life peer]].<ref name=\"Boswell_London_Gazette_Lords\">{{London Gazette |issue=59487 |date=13 July 2010 |page=13285}}</ref><ref name=\"Boswell_Parliament_UK\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-boswell-of-aynho/352 |title = Lord Boswell of Aynho |website=Parliament.uk |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Boswell_Whos_Who\">{{cite web |title=Boswell of Aynho |url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-8174/version/6 |website=ukwhoswho.com |publisher=Who's Who |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nThe son of a farmer, Tim Boswell was educated at [[Marlborough College]] and [[New College, Oxford]], where he obtained a degree in [[Classics]] and a diploma in [[agriculture|agricultural]] [[economics]].<ref name=\"Boswell_Whos_Who\"/>\n\nBoswell was married to Helen Delahay Boswell, n\u00e9e Rees, for 50 years until her death in 2019.<ref name=\"Boswell_Whos_Who\"/><ref name=\"Gazette_Helen_Boswell\">{{cite web |title=Helen Boswell - Deceased Estates |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/3398899 |website=The Gazette (Official Public Record) |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Legacy_Helen_Boswell\">{{cite web |title=Helen Boswell Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/amp/obituaries/thetimes-uk/193460817 |website=Legacy.com |publisher=The Times |accessdate=14 November 2019 |date=23 July 2019}}</ref> They had three daughters together including the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] [[Victoria Prentis]].\n\n==Political career==\n===Conservative Party===\nHe joined the [[Conservative Research Department]] in 1966, becoming head of the economics section in 1974. He stood for [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] at the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]] in [[Rugby (UK Parliament constituency)|Rugby]] but lost by 6,154 votes to [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s [[William Price (Rugby MP)|William Price]].\n\nHe was elected as the Treasurer of the Daventry Conservative Association in 1976 and subsequently its Chairman from 1979-1983. He became a political advisor to the [[Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] [[Michael Jopling, Baron Jopling|Michael Jopling]] for two years from 1984.\n\n===House of Commons===\nBoswell was chosen to contest the Daventry constituency after the sitting Conservative MP and former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Cabinet (government)|Cabinet]] member [[Reg Prentice]] had announced his retirement. Tim Boswell was elected as the Conservative MP for Daventry at the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]] with a majority of 19,690 and held the seat very comfortably since.\n\nTim Boswell's [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]] career began unsurprisingly as a Member of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Agriculture]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]] in 1987. He became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary to the Treasury#Financial Secretaries to the Treasury, 1852-present|Financial Secretary to the Treasury]] [[Peter Lilley]] in 1989. Tim Boswell entered [[John Major]]'s government in 1990 as an [[Whip (politics)|Assistant Government Whip]], following the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]] he was promoted within the Whip's Office and became a Lord Commissioner to the Treasury.\n\nIn December 1992, Tim Boswell was appointed [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department of Education]] and moved in the same position at the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] until the Major government fell at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].\n\nIn opposition Boswell was a spokesman on the [[HM Treasury|Treasury]] in the immediate aftermath of the 1997 election defeat and became a spokesman on [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Trade and Industry]] under [[William Hague]], before speaking on [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Education and Employment]] in 1999 until after the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]]. He became the spokesman for [[Department of Work and Pensions|Work and Pensions]] under the leadership of [[Iain Duncan Smith]], moving briefly to speak on [[Department of Constitutional Affairs|Constitutional Affairs]] in 2003 under [[Michael Howard]] and back to Work and Pensions in 2004, where he remained following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\nOn 31 March 2006, Boswell announced his intention not to contest the subsequent general election, provided it did not take place unexpectedly soon. The Daventry seat was split in two at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], with the northern portion becoming part of a new Daventry constituency and the southern part becoming part of a [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] constituency.\n\nIn May 2009, he was listed by ''The Telegraph'' as one of the \"Saints\" in the expenses scandal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5350793/MPs-expenses-The-saints-Part-iii.html?image=9|title=MPs' Expenses: the saints|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=1 July 2009|location=London|date=19 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter his retirement from the House of Commons the seat remained Conservative under [[Chris Heaton-Harris]].\n\n===House of Lords===\nHe was raised to the [[House of Lords]] as a Conservative [[Life peer]] being created '''Baron Boswell of Aynho''', of [[Aynho]] in the County of [[Northamptonshire]] on 8 July 2010.<ref name=\"Boswell_London_Gazette_Lords\"/> In May 2012, he resigned the Conservative whip after being made Principal Deputy Chairman of Committees in the House. He also became Chairman of the [[European Union Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/25724|title=Lord Boswell of Aynho biography|accessdate=12 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302182756/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/25724|archivedate=2 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/hleu|title=Lords European Union Committee homepage|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nOn 10 March 2016, Boswell was elected a [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London]] (FSA).<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Mar Ballot Results|url=https://www.sal.org.uk/news/2016/03/10-mar-ballot-results/|website=Society of Antiquaries of London|accessdate=16 April 2016|date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Tim+Boswell/ ePolitix.com - Tim Boswell MP]\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-tim-boswell | Tim Boswell }}\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-515,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Tim Boswell MP]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100409065917/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Boswell_Tim.aspx Profile] on Conservative Party website\n*[http://www.daventryconservatives.com Daventry Conservatives]\n*[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/tim_boswell/daventry TheyWorkForYou.com - Tim Boswell MP]\n*[http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Tim_Boswell&mpc=Daventry The Public Whip - Tim Boswell MP] voting record\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/130.stm BBC News - Tim Boswell] profile 15 February 2005\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Daventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Daventry]]\n  | years  = [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n  | before = [[Reg Prentice]]\n  | after  = [[Chris Heaton-Harris]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boswell, Tim}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by David Cameron]]\n[[Category:Contestants on British game shows]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:People from Aynho]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConservative Party:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1979-1983 \u2192 1979\u20131983", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Boswell"}
